    <div class="card">
      <h3>Middle East Travel Tips</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Dress modestly at religious sites:</strong> Covered shoulders and knees are required at mosques throughout the region; women may be asked to cover their hair. At the Western Wall, modest dress is required and men must cover their heads (kippot are provided).</li>
        <li><strong>Photography etiquette:</strong> Always ask permission before photographing individuals, particularly in markets and religious neighborhoods. Photography is prohibited inside many mosques, tombs, and sacred sites — your guide will advise.</li>
        <li><strong>Best time for Egypt:</strong> October through April is the best season — temperatures are comfortable for sightseeing. Summer (June–August) in Egypt is extremely hot, particularly in Upper Egypt.</li>
        <li><strong>Best time for Israel:</strong> March–May and October–November offer the best weather. Shabbat (Friday sunset to Saturday night) affects transportation and restaurants in religious neighborhoods.</li>
        <li><strong>Dietary options:</strong> Halal food is standard throughout Egypt and Turkey. Kosher restaurants are widely available throughout Israel. Many hotels across the region accommodate dietary requirements with advance notice.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

